{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:42:23.166074", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health assessment\n\nSummary\n- The core/distribution/server OSPF fabric appears to be converged and healthy: FRR routers and distribution switches have OSPF routes to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) and to access subnets (10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24). Server-to-server and DNS↔web-server ICMP tests succeed.\n- One access host (host_2_1_1_1) is not configured on the IP network and therefore is isolated/unreachable. This is the primary abnormality discovered.\n- host_1_1_1_1 is configured and can reach the DNS server (and by inference should reach the server farm via OSPF paths).\n\nActions / tests performed\n- Collected full reachability summary (lab-wide ping matrix).\n- Collected network config (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route) from:\n  - host_1_1_1_1\n  - host_2_1_1_1\n  - switch_dist_1_1\n  - switch_dist_2_1\n  - switch_server_access\n  - router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3\n- Performed targeted pings:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 ⇨ dns_server (4 packets)\n  - host_2_1_1_1 ⇨ dns_server (4 packets)\n\nKey observed outputs (selected)\n- host_1_1_1_1\n  - eth0: 10.1.1.2/24\n  - default route: via 10.1.1.1\n  - Ping to dns_server 10.200.0.2: 4/4 success, rtt avg ~3.9 ms\n- host_2_1_1_1\n  - eth0: interface up, but no IPv4 address shown (ifconfig/ip_addr show no inet)\n  - ip route: empty\n  - Ping to dns_server: “ping: connect: Network is unreachable”\n- switch_dist_1_1 (distribution for 10.1.1.0/24)\n  - br0: 10.1.1.1/24 (gateway for host_1)\n  - eth0: 172.16.0.7/31 (link toward core)\n  - OSPF-learned routes present (10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.6)\n- switch_dist_2_1 (distribution for 10.2.1.0/24)\n  - br0: 10.2.1.1/24\n  - eth0: 172.16.0.9/31\n  - OSPF-learned routes present (10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.8)\n- switch_server_access (server-access switch)\n  - br0: 10.200.0.1/24\n  - eth5: 172.16.0.11/31 to core_3\n  - OSPF routes present and servers (10.200.0.3–.6) reachable\n- router_core_1 / router_core_2 / router_core_3\n  - Interfaces and /31 addresses match topology\n  - OSPF tables show routes for 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, 10.200.0.0/24 across the core\n  - No signs of OSPF flap or missing networks in the routing output\n\nAnomalies and localization\n1) Host IP configuration / reachability failure\n   - Device: host_2_1_1_1 (access host on 10.2.1.0/24)\n   - Symptom: Interface is up at the link layer but has no IPv4 address and no default route. Attempts to ping central DNS (10.200.0.2) fail locally with “Network is unreachable”.\n   - Evidence:\n     - host_2_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip_addr: no inet address assigned to eth0.\n     - ip route output on host_2_1_1_1 is empty.\n     - ping from host_2_1_1_1 to dns_server returned immediate network unreachable.\n   - Localization: Problem is local to host_2_1_1_1 (host-level configuration or provisioning). The distribution switch (switch_dist_2_1) and core routing show normal OSPF reachability for 10.2.1.0/24 and the rest of the network.\n\n2) No other device-level abnormalities detected in tests\n   - Server farm (10.200.0.0/24): inter-server pings and dns_server → web_server pings are successful (0% loss, low RTT).\n   - Distribution switches br0 and core routers have expected IPs and OSPF routes; multiple cores show symmetric view of networks.\n   - host_1_1_1_1 is configured, has a default gateway, and successfully pings the DNS server (4/4 success).\n\nRoot-cause analysis (most likely)\n- host_2_1_1_1 is isolated because it lacks an IPv4 address (and therefore lacks a default gateway). Given the network uses statically addressed hosts (per description) this is a host configuration issue: host_2 was not assigned its static IP (or lost it) or DHCP (if used) did not assign an address. The immediate root cause is local misconfiguration on host_2_1_1_1 (absent/incorrect IPv4 settings).\n- There is no evidence of an OSPF area/core convergence issue, link down on core-to-distribution links, or server farm routing problem. OSPF routing tables on all three core routers and the distribution switches show correct routes to access and server networks.\n\nImpact assessment\n- host_2_1_1_1: full network isolation (cannot reach DNS, servers, or other networks).\n- Other hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 and server farm are unaffected; internal server-to-server, DNS-to-webserver, and host_1 to DNS connectivity are functioning.\n- Network fabric (core + distribution + server access) appears operational and providing reachability between segments.\n\nAdditional notes / observations\n- host_1_1_1_1 shows a single dropped RX packet in interface statistics — low count, not currently indicating a systemic link error.\n- OSPF tables show expected multipath entries in some places; these are consistent with the triangular core topology and do not indicate instability in the collected snapshots.\n- The initial lab-wide reachability summary included several \"unknown\" entries for host→web tests; those \"unknown\" statuses correspond to tests that were not run rather than failures. Where explicit tests were run (host_1→dns, host_2→dns, server↔server), results are as described above.\n\nConclusion\n- Network fabric and routing are healthy and converged; server farm and DNS are reachable from core/distribution and at least one access host (host_1).\n- The clear abnormality is a single misconfigured/unnumbered host (host_2_1_1_1) which is locally isolated due to missing IPv4 configuration. This local host configuration issue is the root cause of that host’s lack of connectivity.\n\nIf you want, I can run additional confirmation tests (for example: attempt host_1 -> web_server pings/HTTP tests, confirm ARP tables, or inspect host_2 interface/link-layer details) — but I will not propose or apply remedies unless you request them.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 16159, "output_tokens": 2919, "total_tokens": 19078, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 3840}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1280}}}
